One-Hot Encoding
Categorical data (like Brand or BU) cannot be used directly in mathematical models. One-hot encoding creates a new binary column for each unique category. That is why we convert categorical data into dummy variables so that to use for analysis purpose further.

Impact: The original 13 columns expanded to 87 columns after encoding variables like SKU, Brand, and Model.

Importance: This allows the model to treat each category independently without assuming an artificial numerical order (which would happen with simple label encoding).

5. Conclusion
Summary of Key Findings
This analysis provides a comprehensive overview of the sales dataset, covering descriptive statistics, data visualization, and essential preprocessing steps like standardization and one-hot encoding.

Product Diversity: The dataset captures a wide variety of products, from high-frequency/low-cost FMCG items to low-frequency/high-cost Mobiles.

Pricing Strategy: Discounts are widespread, typically hovering around 15%, but the absolute discount amount varies wildly based on product price.

Data Readiness: Preprocessing steps like standardization and one-hot encoding are essential for this dataset before moving to predictive modeling, as they handle the high variance in scales and the diverse categorical nature of the features.

 
